orms of cancer and the second leading cause of cancer death. It is more prevalent in males than females; however, prevalence has been increasing in both genders over the last two decades (Ellison, L.F., Wilkins, K. 2012). Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is a primary cancer of the hepatocytes that is typically a progression from the benign hepatocellular adenoma (HCA). The most common risk factor for developing hepatocellular carcinoma is chronic liver injury and inflammation (caused by persistent infection, fatty liver disease, or chemical exposure). This disease is almost always lethal in the absence of extreme intervention measures (e.g., surgery, liver transplant).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:21:45 +0000 2026"}